# Backend and API design

These rules apply once a project adds a server, API route, or service layer. They are
deliberately framework-agnostic (Express, Fastify, Next.js route handlers, Hono, etc. all
qualify) — pick one stack per project and record the choice in `90-project-context.mdc`,
do not mix backend frameworks within a project.

Input validation, secrets, and authorization are covered in `10-security-popia.mdc` —
this file does not repeat them, only adds API-shape conventions on top.

## Contract first

- Define the request/response shape before writing the handler. Prefer a typed schema
  (Zod, the OpenAPI/JSON Schema equivalent) as the single source of truth for both
  validation and generated types — do not hand-maintain a TypeScript interface and a
  validator separately, they will drift.
- Version breaking changes in the URL or a header (`/v1/...` or `Accept-Version`), never
  silently change a response shape that existing clients depend on.

## Error responses

- Every error response uses one consistent shape across the whole API, e.g.
  `{ error: { code, message, details? } }`. Never return a bare string or a stack trace.
- Map errors to correct HTTP status codes: `400` validation, `401` unauthenticated,
  `403` unauthorized, `404` not found, `409` conflict, `422` semantically invalid,
  `429` rate-limited, `5xx` server fault. Do not return `200` with an error payload.
- Never leak internals in an error message returned to the client (stack traces, SQL,
  file paths, library versions). Log the detail server-side; return a generic message
  and a correlation/request ID the client can quote when reporting an issue.

## Idempotency and safety

- `GET`/`HEAD`/`OPTIONS` must never mutate state.
- Mutating endpoints that may be retried by a client (payments, submissions) must accept
  an idempotency key and return the original result on a repeated request with the same
  key, rather than performing the action twice.
- `PUT` is idempotent (full replace); `PATCH` is a partial update; `POST` creates or
  performs a non-idempotent action. Do not use `POST` for an operation that is actually
  a replace.

## Pagination and payload size

- Any endpoint that can return an unbounded list must paginate (cursor-based preferred
  over offset for anything that can grow past a few thousand rows). Document the default
  and maximum page size.
- Reject request bodies above a sane size limit at the framework/proxy level, not after
  full deserialization.

## Rate limiting and abuse prevention

- Public or authenticated-but-untrusted endpoints must have a rate limit. State the
  limit (requests per window per key) in the route's documentation or a comment.
- Rate-limit by an identity the caller cannot freely change (user ID, API key) wherever
  one is available; fall back to IP only for fully anonymous endpoints.

## Hard stops

- Do not design an endpoint without first writing down its request/response contract.
- Do not return inconsistent error shapes across different routes in the same API.
- Do not implement a mutating endpoint that can be safely retried without an idempotency
  story.
- Do not skip authorization checks because "the UI doesn't expose this" — every
  protected operation must be enforced server-side (see `10-security-popia.mdc`).
